Testing would involve taking random samples of these AI tools and testing them in an environment that simulates the real world.

 Following the successful conclusion of such tests, the machines in question can then be rolled out for the general market. 

#ArtificialIntelligence

It would even be absurd to suggest that a chatbot should be tested by a regulator before it is rolled out.

 These tests would be focused on AI applications that are capable of physical harm. 

#ArtificialIntelligence

The length of time and nature of the tests would vary depending on how much the application in question relies on AI.

 For instance, a self-driving car (which is essentially a robot) relies on AI to a larger extent, compared to a chatbot. 

#ArtificialIntelligence

In the aftermath of the Japan incident that I mentioned earlier, the Ministry of Labour reacted by enacting stricter regulations to govern the use of robots in the workplace.

Such regulations could include mandatory testing periods for AI applications. 

#ArtificialIntelligence

In the same vein, the personal risks that AI might pose can be mitigated by the enactment of guidelines to regulate how AI is used in the workplace and by consumers. 

#ArtificialIntelligence

Unlike what science fiction might suggest, AI is not some kind of ‚ÄòTerminator-in-waiting‚Äô that will one day begin a revolt against its human masters. 

AI is simply an advanced tool, which is susceptible to glitches that may cause injury. 

#ArtificialIntelligence

Most of the programming that drives the way robots function is implemented with machine learning, a sub-field of AI.

Although this fear is valid, it does not paint a general picture of AI.

The onus lies on AI developers to collect a wider pool of data, that effectively represents the diversity of the people the technology will serve.

 This may not eliminate bias or instances of bad decisions entirely, but it will mitigate them.

#ArtificialIntelligence

So, when next you hear that AI can make decisions that will affect our lives negatively, remember that it is not the fault of the technology.

 AI is not inherently good or bad. It is at best, amoral. 

#ArtificialIntelligence

Even in scenarios AI acts autonomously because human supervision would slow it down (for instance, self-driving cars), remember that the data and rules by which it runs were developed by humans.

#ArtificialIntelligence

Fully autonomous AI systems that do not require human supervision at all have not gone mainstream yet. 

#ArtificialIntelligence

But the fault here doesn‚Äôt lie with AI, nor does it lie with data. Data doesn‚Äôt create nor collect itself.

 Humans do. In most cases, these AI systems only give recommendations that may or may not be accepted by a human operator.

#ArtificialIntelligence
